  "text": "Several examples of naturally occurring 3Ј-transduction events were identified previously as mutagenic L1 insertions, in which additional (non-L1) sequences were incorporated downstream from each newly transposed L1 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). Transduction of 3Ј-flanking sequence by engineered L1 elements also readily occurs in HeLa cells, and can be driven by either the cytomegalovirus promoter, or the native L1 promoter; notably, transposition efficiency is higher when a strong polyadenylation signal is introduced downstream from the L1 [CITATION_4] . An important open question remains-how efficiently does L1-driven 3Ј transduction occur naturally in the human genome? Opportunities to observe abnormal human phenotypes caused by 3Ј-transducing L1 insertions may be extremely limited because only a small fraction of the human genome is currently attributed to genes and upstream regulatory regions. In this study, we took advantage of the tremendous sequence production by the Human Genome Project to computationally estimate the extent of naturally occurring L1-driven 3Ј transduction (Fig.1) .",
